data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Issue in .NET 8 |
|----------|---------|-----------------|
| `Stop()` → `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control-flow cleanup | Never thrown in .NET 8 — rollback silently skipped |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` in `Stop()` | Blind wait | Works, but `Thread.Join(timeout)` is correct |

## Critical Pitfall: Silent Data Loss

The **most dangerous** issue: `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown in .NET 8, so the `catch` block containing `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` becomes **dead code**. If `GetNextItem()` blocks indefinitely, `Stop()` will wait 2 seconds, call `Abort()`, get a `PlatformNotSupportedException`, and the thread keeps running — no rollback, no shutdown.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back any partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // Loop condition will exit naturally
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish its current item
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time — it's stuck in uncooperative code.
            // Log a warning. The thread is marked IsBackground so it will
            // be torn down on process exit. For stricter control, move
            // uncooperative work to a child process and use Process.Kill.
            Console.Error.WriteLine("Worker thread did not exit within timeout.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitHandle`, async I/O) so blocked threads actually wake up |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal — no `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard prevents swallowing unrelated exceptions |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed — loop condition exits naturally | No abort to reset; cancellation is checked at the top of the loop |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))` | Returns early if thread exits before timeout; returns `bool` indicating success |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` owns timers/callbacks and must be disposed |

## You Must Also Update `GetNextItem`

This is the **most commonly missed step**. If `GetNextItem` blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection` or socket), cancellation stalls there. It must accept and honor the token:

```csharp
// Before — blocks indefinitely, immune to cancellation
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until an item is available
}

// After — wakes up when cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep`, `WaitOne`, or similar:

```csharp
// Replace Thread.Sleep with cancellation-aware wait
// Before: Thread.Sleep(1000);
// After:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000); // returns immediately if token is cancelled
```

## Key Pitfalls for This Migration

1. **Token must flow through the entire call chain** — if `ProcessItem` calls sub-methods with blocking I/O, pass `token` to every level. One missing link and cancellation stalls.

2. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — only catch it at this top-level loop. Inner methods should let it propagate.

3. **`CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`** — failing to dispose leaks timer handles. Always use `using` or implement `IDisposable` on the owning class.

4. **No true forced kill exists in .NET 8** — if the thread runs uncooperative code (native call, third-party library), `Cancel()` has no effect. Move such work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`.
